article.headline: Behind Frierson and Ford, Louisiana Tech rolls Fresno

images.name: Frierson_Trina 031503 vertic top

article.linkText: No. 6 Louisiana State has no trouble winning WAC title
article.story:
TULSA, Okla. (AP) -- Louisiana Tech capped its perfect play in
the Western Athletic Conference with another tournament title.

<photo1>

	   Trina Frierson scored 18 points and Cheryl Ford had 25 rebounds
as sixth-ranked Louisiana Tech beat Fresno State 89-57 to win
its second consecutive WAC tournament Saturday.

	   Louisiana Tech (29-2) completely dominated the game and won its
27th in a row to extend the nation's longest winning streak. The
Lady Techsters went 18-0 in the conference during the regular
season.

	   Coach Kurt Budke hopes the victory translates into a high seed going
into the NCAA tournament.

	   ''We talk all the time about gaining more respect around the
country,'' he said.

	   Louisiana Tech led by as many as 35 in the second half.

	   Ford broke the WAC single-game record of 19 rebounds before the
halfway point of the second half. She also scored 14 points.

	   Tasha Crain added 17 for the Lady Techsters, Erica Smith had 14
and Amisha Carter scored 11.

	   Budke said his team is playing its best basketball.

	   ''There are a lot of people that will hang with us for 25 to 30
minutes, but soon the pressure gets to them,'' he said. ''We are
creating a lot of offense off of our defense. The development of
Tasha Crain has been a big key also.''

	   No. 3 seed Fresno State (19-12) was outmuscled and outsized. The
Bulldogs shot only 28 percent from the field, going 4-for-16 from
3-point range, and were outrebounded 56-41.

	   Fresno State coach Stacy Johnson-Klein, who helped recruit many
of Tech's players when she and Budke were assistants under former
coach Leon Barmore, was impressed with the Lady Techsters.

	   ''They're powerful, they're strong, they're smart, they can
shoot the ball. There's nothing they can't do,'' she said. ''They
can defend. It's tough to beat a team like that.''

	   Louisiana Tech scored first, then went on a 12-2 run to take a
17-6 lead. Fresno State's Veronica Mack made a basket and 3-pointer
to close the Bulldogs to seven points at 20-13. But Tech blazed
ahead, and Fresno State never got close again.

	   Lindsay Logan led the Bulldogs with 15 points, even though she
had difficulty penetrating the post. Tiffany Simon added 13 points.

	   It was Fresno State's first trip to the WAC tournament final,
coming just a year after the Bulldogs completed one of the worst
seasons in school history at 9-20. Fresno State finished with a
winning record for the first time since 1996-97.

	   Johnson-Klein predicted that the team next year will challenge
Louisiana Tech's WAC dominance.

	   ''We don't have the talent obviously that Tech has, but we have
the heart,'' she said.
